<title type="html"><![CDATA[Putting 2 CPU (or PPU's) in a NES]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4366&amp;p=36938#p36938"><![CDATA[
I had my nes working with a stock ntsc ppu and a play choice 10 rgb ppu.<br />All I did was lift the power pin and rgb pins from a socket I soldered to the top of one ppu. I then switch the 5 volts to the chip I wanted to be active.<br />For the hell of it I powered both on.  I got no picture but I could hear the game running and it sounded like it ran 2X faster.<br /><br /><br />The chips/eproms that people used in Xboxes  have a chip enable pin that is tied to a pull up circuit<br />to ensure the chip stays in a stand by mode.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3503">acem77</a> — Tue Sep 09, 2008 10:01 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
